04047nam a22005655i 9780226584478DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265844787 a10.7208/97802265844782doi  a(DE-B1597)524336  a(OCoLC)1061860856  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHD593b.F58 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a333.309412231 aFitz-Gibbon, Desmond, eauthor.10aMarketable Values :bInventing the Property Market in Modern Britain /cDesmond Fitz-Gibbon. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b20 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Locating the Property Market -- t1. The Marketplace -- t2. Market People -- t3. Calculating the Market -- t4. States of Marketability -- t5. The Limits of Marketability -- tConclusion: "Property for the Million" -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea that land should be-or even could be-treated like any other commodity has not always been a given. For much of British history, land was bought and sold in ways that emphasized its role in complex networks of social obligation and political power, and that resisted comparisons with more easily transacted and abstract markets. Fast-forward to today, when house-flipping is ubiquitous and references to the fluctuating property market fill the news. How did we get here?   In Marketable Values, Desmond Fitz-Gibbon seeks to answer that question. He tells the story of how Britons imagined, organized, and debated the buying and selling of land from the mid-eighteenth to the early twentieth century. In a society organized around the prestige of property, the desire to commodify land required making it newly visible through such spectacles  as public auctions, novel professions like auctioneering, and real estate journalism. As Fitz-Gibbon shows, these innovations sparked impassioned debates on where, when, and how to demarcate the limits of a market society. As a result of these collective efforts, the real estate business became legible to an increasingly attentive public and a lynchpin of modern economic life.   Drawing on an eclectic range of sources-from personal archives and estate correspondence to building designs, auction handbills, and newspapers-Marketable Values explores the development of the British property market and the seminal role it played in shaping the relationship we have to property around the world today.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aReal property auctionszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aReal propertyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aReal propertyzGreat BritainxMarketingxHistoryy19th century. 4aBritain. 4acommerce. 4acultural history. 4aproperty market. 4areal estate market. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226584478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226584478.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles